Introduction

Since the inception of Pokemon, first released for the GameBoy handheld console, there has been a myriad of adaptations and creations related to this virtual world. Some examples include video games, trading cards, television shows, and movies, demonstrating its popularity and fan base. https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/History_of_Pok%C3%A9mon

Pokemon, originally called “Pocket Monsters”, was created by Satoshi Tajiri. As a child, he would catch insects and tadpoles and wanted to give other children the same thrill in the form of a game. The initial game, Pokemon Red and Green, was released in Japan and allowed players worldwide to trade, catch, and train 151 creatures with the goal to become a Pokemon master. Following this, Media Factory released a Pokemon Trading Card Game, skyrocketing the popularity of Pokemon as a whole. Within the next two years, manga interpretations, anime series, magazines, and even stores were created. The success of Pokemon in Japan lead to it being released worldwide, using the slogan Gotta Catch ‘em All! The Pokemon game is role-playing and turn-based, with each of the Pokemon having a type. When Pokemon Red and Green (or Red and Blue) was released, there were 15 types:

  • Normal
  • Fire
  • Water
  • Electric
  • Grass
  • Ice
  • Fighting
  • Poison
  • Ground
  • Flying
  • Psychic
  • Bug
  • Rock
  • Ghost
  • Dragon

Since then, three types have been added: Dark Steel Fairy

In the world of Pokemon, a Pokemon’s type indicates characteristics and traits that affect the interactions, strategies, and gameplay of each battle. Each type has strengths and weaknesses, having high effectiveness against certain types, but also low effectiveness against others. Here is a brief summary of the strengths and weaknesses of each type:

Normal: Considered to be the most basic type, and having no elemental affinity, this type is not super effective or weak against any other type.

Fire: Has the elemental attribute of fire Strong against Steel, Bug, Ice, and Grass types Weak against Dragon, Rock, and Water types

Water: Associated with the element of water Strong against Ground, Fire, and Rock types Weak against Grass and Electric types

Grass: Associated with plants Strong against Rock, Ground, and Water types Weak against Fire, Flying, Poison, Ice, and Bug types

Electric: Associated with electricity (surprise surprise) Strong against Flying and Water types Weak against Ground types

Ice: Associated with ice/freezing Strong against Dragon, Grass, Ground, and Flying types Weak against Steel, Fighting, Fire, and Rock types

Fighting: Associated with physical fighting (and perhaps martial arts) Strong against Ice, Normal, Dark, Steel, and Rock types Weak against Fairy, Psychic, Flying, and even some other Fighting types

Poison: Associated with venom and toxic abilities Strong against Fairy and Grass types Weak against Psychic, Ground, and other poison types Cannot affect Steel types

Ground: Associated with the earth Strong against Fire, Rock, Steel, Poison, and Electric types Weak against Grass, Ice, and Water types Unaffected by Electric-type attacks

Flying: Able to fly, often birdlike in nature Strong against Fighting, Grass, and Bug types Weak against Ice, Electric, and Rock types

Psychic: Associated with the mind, mental abilities, and psychic powers Strong against Poison and Fighting types Weak against Dark, Bug, and Ghost types

Bug: Associated with arthropods and insects Strong against Psychic, Grass, and Dark types Weak against Flying, Fire, and Rock types

Rock: Associated with being durable Strong against Flying, Fire, and Ice types Weak against Grass, Water, Fighting, Steel, and Ground types

Ghost: Have ghostly or supernatural abilities Strong against Psychic and other Ghost types Weak against Dark and other Ghost types Immune to Fighting and Normal attacks

Dragon: Represent dragons Strong against other Dragon types Weak against Fairy, Ice, and other Dragon types

Dark: Represents the night, darkness, and trickery Strong against Ghost and Psychic types Weak against Fairy, Bug, and Fighting types

Steel: Represent metal and have metallic bodies Strong against Rock, Ice, and Fairy types Weak against Ground, Fire, and Fighting types

Fairy: Associated with being mythical and fairies Strong against Dragon, Dark, and Fighting types Weak against Poison and Steel types Immune to Dragon types

Since there are so many overlapping type strengths and weaknesses we thought we would collect, clean, and display our data based on types.

With the previous information all collected, we can go onto a new website, https://pokemondb.net/pokedex/, and collect various other data. Once we scrape the data, we parse it using BeautifulSoup and filter out information by the table, with the class “vitals-table”. For all Pokemon we extract the primary and secondary types, height in meters, weight in kilograms, catch rate, base happiness, base experience, growth rate, gender variability and egg cycles.

In [ ]:
def get_pokemon_data(pokemon_name: str):
    pokemon_name = pokemon_name.replace(' ', '-').replace('♂', '-m').replace('♀', '-f').replace('.','').replace("'", '').replace('é','e').replace(':','')
    link = 'https://pokemondb.net/pokedex/' + pokemon_name.lower() + '/'
    data = requests.get(link).content
    bs = bs4.BeautifulSoup(data, 'html.parser')
    stats_data_raw = bs.findAll('table', {'class': 'vitals-table'})
    stats_data = pd.read_html(str(stats_data_raw))
    types = stats_data[0][1][1].split(' ')
    type = types[0]
    type2 = None
    if len(types) == 2:
        type2 = types[1]
    height = stats_data[0][1][3].split()[0]
    weight = stats_data[0][1][4].split()[0]
    catch_rate = stats_data[1][1][1].split(' ')[0]
    base_happiness = stats_data[1][1][2].split(' ')[0]
    base_exp = stats_data[1][1][3]
    growth_rate = stats_data[1][1][4]
    gender = "Genderless" if stats_data[2][1][1] == "Genderless" else stats_data[2][1][1].split(' ')[0]
    egg_cycles = stats_data[2][1][2].split(' ')[0]
    return {"Name": pokemon_name, "primary_type": type, "secondary_type": type2, "Height": height, "Weight": weight, "catch_rate": catch_rate
            , "base_happiness": base_happiness, "base_exp": base_exp, "growth_rate": growth_rate,
            "gender": gender, "egg_cycles": egg_cycles}

pokemon_data = []
for pokemon in pokemon_table['Name']:
    pokemon_data.append(get_pokemon_data(pokemon))

pokemon_stats = pd.DataFrame(pokemon_data)

We then grab all of the possibilities for abilities in the pokemon world. An ability is a special power that a Pokemon has that affects how it battles. Abilities give Pokemon (or their opponents) new effects, like increasing or decreasing a/all stats, changing the weather or battleground condition, or even protecting it from status conditions. Each species of Pokemon generally has an ability or two which are specific to that species. These abilities are capable of dramatically impacting a Pokemon’s overall performance in battle.

These abilities add extra complexity to pokemon battles. For example, there is an ability called “Levitate” which disallows attacks from any Ground type Pokemon moves.

To obtain the names of these abilities, we once again parse information using BeautifulSoup, from https://pokemondb.net/ability. We get the data with the id “abilities”, and process it further.

We take the abilities, and parse it to the original massive table of Pokemon. For example, where the ability used to read “solar power blaze”, it now reads as a list, containing two elements, “Solar Power”, and “Blaze”.

In [ ]:
abilities_list = abilities_table["Name"].tolist()
def split_abilities(abilities):
    string_pairs = []
    string_list = abilities.split()
    for combination in list(map(' '.join, itertools.permutations(string_list, 2))):
        if combination in abilities_list:
            string_pairs.append(combination)
    for string in string_list:
        if string in abilities_list:
            string_pairs.append(string)
    #include case for three worded abilities
    for combination in list(map(' '.join, itertools.permutations(string_list, 3))):
        if combination in abilities_list:
            string_pairs.append(combination)
    return string_pairs

#Apply split abilities to the abilities column
full_info["Abilities"] = full_info["Abilities"].apply(split_abilities)

We then added the stat “Base Stat” to the list. This stat represents the overall strength of a Pokemon and is obtained by combining all 6 major stats. These stats are HP, Attack, Defense, Special Attack, and Special Defense.

In [ ]:
def base_stat():
    base_stat = []
    for index, row in full_info.iterrows():
        base_stat.append(int(row["HP"]) + int(row["Att"]) + int(row["Def"]) + int(row["S.Att"]) + int(row["S.Def"]) + int(row["Spd"]))
    return base_stat

full_info["Base Stat"] = base_stat()

Which type is the strongest overall? Which is the weakest?

How would we define "strongest" and "weakest"? Let's use the average base stat of each type to determine this.

In [ ]:
primary_type = full_info["primary_type"].unique()
average_base_stat = []
for type in primary_type:
    average_base_stat.append(full_info[full_info["primary_type"] == type]["Base Stat"].mean())

#Show scatter plot of primary type and average base stat

We next try to find the strongest and weakest overall pokemon type. We do this by finding the average base stats of each type, and then graph it on a scatter plot. Dragon type has the highest, and the lowest belongs to bug type.

Next we attempt to create a machine learning algorithm which takes in a pokemon’s base stat, catch rate, happiness, experience, height and weight. We use a RandomForestClassifier from sklearn, and fit the model with a training set. We predict it on a test set and get an accuracy of about 25%. We test a few pokemon to guess their type and get a fair amount right. Unfortunately the model isn’t 100% accurate.

In [ ]:
# Here we copy the dataframe with all of the data and manipulate so we can create a model to classify Pokemon types
df = full_info.copy(deep=True)
df.drop(['Abilities','gender', 'growth_rate', 'secondary_type', 'No.'], inplace=True, axis=1)

X = df.drop(['Name','primary_type'], axis=1)
Y = df['primary_type']
X_encoded = pd.get_dummies(X)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_encoded, Y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
selected_features = ['HP', 'Att', 'Def', 'S.Att', 'S.Def', 'Spd', 'Height', 'Weight', 'catch_rate', 'base_happiness', 'base_exp']
model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
model.fit(X_train[selected_features], y_train)
y_pred = model.predict(X_test[selected_features])
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy}")

# Function to test our model on any Pokemon
def test_pokemon_type(name):
    test_pokemon = full_info[full_info['Name'] == name]
    test_pokemon.drop(['Name', 'Abilities','gender', 'growth_rate', 'secondary_type', 'No.', 'primary_type', 'Base Stat', 'secondary_type', 'egg_cycles'], inplace=True, axis=1)
    prediction = model.predict(test_pokemon)
    print("The type prediction for ", name, " is ", prediction)
